caption: I‚Äôm not sure there‚Äôs ever been a book like Dear New York. Designed as a gift to the city, one hundred percent of royalties are being reinvested back into the city in the form of public art and donations to NYC charities. I put my whole heart into this one, and early reviews agree: it is the most beautiful, most lovingly created Humans of New York book. At nearly 500 full-color pages, it features hundreds of stories that have never been seen before. I will not be receiving a penny from Dear New York, but I‚Äôve never wanted more badly for you to own a book of mine. It was a labor of love. And nothing would make me happier than for as many of you to experience it as possible. I think for all artists, this is something much more valuable than money. ‚ÄòDear New York‚Äô is coming out next month. If you‚Äôre planning to get a copy, please consider pre ordering today through the link in bio.

caption: ‚ÄúOne time we were playing in the yard of the school, and the gates were open, and the watchman, he was so precious, he was praying. So we packed our bags and ran for it. There were five of us girls. The watchman saw us and began to call us back, and all of them ran back, except for me. I kept running. The only thing is‚ÄîI literally had nowhere to go. My uncles worked in the middle of the city. If I went there, they would see me. Nothing ever happens in Gaza City without everyone finding out and everyone talking about it. So I just went home. That‚Äôs the thing about this place; it‚Äôs the only place I feel like I belong, but it was always so suffocating. There wasn‚Äôt even space for a teenager to be rebellious. I think the craziest thing we did was paint on walls. Like all teenagers we were convinced that everything was so dark, and the world was ending. So we‚Äôd graffiti Pink Floyd and Cold Play lyrics onto walls: ‚ÄòLights will guide you home.‚Äô Meanwhile home is literally two blocks away, two streets away. The entire neighborhood is rubble now. Honestly I don‚Äôt even like to talk about the past because it feels like the world keeps begging us to prove that we‚Äôre human beings. And if we could only do that, if we could prove that we once lived in nice houses, and listened to Cold Play, then we could prove that we deserve to live and eat and exist and survive. I hate it. I hate pity so much, because it belittles the person you‚Äôre pitying. Please don‚Äôt feel sorry for me. Don‚Äôt feel sorry for us. We don‚Äôt need you, I promise. We don‚Äôt need anyone. We have farmers with farmlands, but they cannot harvest their own farmlands without being shot. We have fishermen who can collect fish from the sea, but they‚Äôre banned from using the sea. We have these beautiful, beautiful cuisines. We can feed ourselves. Just let us, we‚Äôve reached that point. Just let us. Don‚Äôt feel sorry for us. Feel sorry for yourselves, that you‚Äôre living in a country that is arming Israel, that is sending weapons overseas to kill children. Your bombs are killing children. If that bothers you, then don‚Äôt feel sorry for us. Feel sorry for yourself. That you don‚Äôt have enough say in your own country to stop it.‚Äù

caption: I‚Äôm holding a photography contest open to all kids in NYC. It‚Äôs easy to participate: the child merely needs to take a portrait of someone they believe deserves to be honored, and write a statement explaining this person‚Äôs impact on their life or community. Every student submitting an entry will be included in an online art gallery. Three hundred submissions will be professionally framed and hung in a two-week photography exhibit in Grand Central‚Äôs Vanderbilt Hall, alongside the work of professional photographers. After the exhibit each selected student will have their framed portrait mailed back to them, along with two $50 gift cards to a local independent bookstore‚Äîone for the child, and one for the person they chose to honor. On the surface this is a photography exhibition, but I‚Äôm hopeful it will create thousands of meaningful connections between the children of New York and the adults who show up in their lives. This exhibit is being staged in partnership with the NYC Public Schools Arts Office, but is open to all the city‚Äôs children. So please help spread the word to any NYC children and educators in your life. Full contest info can be found through the link in bio.

caption: ‚ÄúWe started with eight kids from the projects; my son and seven other kids. But that first year we grew to 75 kids. Now we‚Äôve got different teams, different coaches. I pay for a lot of this stuff myself. It‚Äôs sad, because some of the parents‚Ä¶ well, maybe they just don‚Äôt have money. Because I refuse to think that they don‚Äôt care. Because if you don‚Äôt care, and you just leave them in the street‚Äîso much can happen, so easily. And I don‚Äôt want that for them. I want them to do something with their life. They count on me. So if they count on me, if they‚Äôre able to show up, how does it look for me not to show up for them? I have to show up for them. I have to show up for them. Some of these kids have been with me four years. It‚Äôs been a great pleasure to watching them grow: going from not knowing how to catch, to knowing how to catch, to getting baseball ready. But baseball is just the vessel to get them in. As you can see, we don‚Äôt just come play baseball and leave. We barbecue every two weeks. We have a lot of events with the kids: trunk-or-treat, Christmas giveaways, birthday parties. It‚Äôs not just come play ball, I‚Äôll see you next week. It‚Äôs everything. It‚Äôs a family. Let‚Äôs grow this into where you can have friends for the rest of your life. There‚Äôs a lot of troubled kids getting into fights and doing things like that. But if they become your friend, you don‚Äôt want to fight with your friend. You want to protect your friend.‚Äù

caption: The first copies of Dear New York have arrived. This one is deeply personal; holding it in my hand is like holding three years of my life. it opens with a longform HONY story‚Äî think Tanqueray, think Detra, think Venus‚Äî except this time it‚Äôs the story of my own attempt to capture the people of this city. The book then expands into four hundred full-color portraits and stories. Unlike previous Humans of New York books: 75 percent of these stories have not been shared online. Dear New York was lovingly created to be the most special thing that‚Äôs ever come out of Humans of New York. It will make you think, it will make you laugh, it will make you cry. It‚Äôs my love letter to this city, and I can‚Äôt wait to share it with you this October. But if you could do me a favor: if you think you‚Äôll be getting Dear New York this fall, consider locking in your order now.
